{
  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game is driven by asymmetric private values on red and blue chips, with common-value green chips. Bear strongly values blue ($1) and moderately values red ($0.60). Buffalo and Goose both value blue only modestly (Buffalo $0.70, Goose $0.10) and red very little ($0.10). All value green at $0.50. Public information reveals that green is exactly $0.50 for everyone, but red and blue are only known privately, creating uncertainty about who values which color most. Players know their own valuations, see others’ chip holdings and trade history, and can compute their own surplus for any proposed trade, but cannot directly see others’ values.\n\nGiven these valuations, Bear is the likely high-value buyer of blue and a relatively higher-value holder of red compared to the others. Buffalo’s best opportunities are to convert low-value red (for Buffalo) into blue or green at reasonable terms, and to avoid giving away blue too cheaply. Goose, who values both red and blue at only $0.10, is nearly indifferent between red and blue in private value and will mainly look to gain disposable chips (especially green) or risk-free improvements while avoiding clear losses. Because everyone knows that green is worth $0.50 to all, green trades are focal and low-ambiguity: exchanging green against red or blue will be hard unless the other side believes the color they get is higher private value.\n\nThe core strategic uncertainty is about the private values of red and blue. Bear knows that blue is extremely valuable for herself and will try to acquire it cheaply, but doesn’t know others’ valuations. Buffalo knows red is almost worthless and will try to sell red at a gain, but cannot tell whether Bear or Goose values red more. Goose sees both red and blue as almost worthless and may be reluctant to part with green, but may accept offers that increase her total chip count if losses are small or zero.\n\nBehaviorally, all three players show relatively low to medium ultimatum rejection thresholds and moderate fairness norms. That suggests they are not extremely aggressive; they will look for clearly positive-sum or at least non-exploitative deals, but are unlikely to reject small positive gains out of spite. With only three rounds and one proposal each per round, time is limited: players have mild incentives to experiment with information-revealing proposals early while preserving flexibility for better deals later. However, because each proposal can be accepted by either of the two responders and the realized partner is random when there are multiple acceptances, proposers must design trades that are acceptable regardless of which counterpart they match with, or else restrict themselves to deals likely to be accepted by exactly one responder.\n\nOverall, the likely pattern is: Round 0 features exploratory but cautious trades, especially involving red for green or blue at relatively conservative ratios. As the game proceeds, Bear will attempt to accumulate blue while giving up some combination of red and green, and Buffalo and Goose will be willing to take small gains in green or convert their least-valued colors while avoiding large, clearly negative trades. Coordination problems, the random tie-breaking, and valuation uncertainty make some mutually beneficial trades fail, especially early, but at least a few modestly positive-sum trades are expected to go through over three rounds.",
