  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features symmetric initial endowments (10 RED, 10 BLUE, 10 GREEN each) but asymmetric private values on RED and BLUE. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone, so surplus comes mainly from reallocating RED and BLUE to players who value them more. badger values both RED and BLUE highly ($0.80 each), camel moderately prefers RED ($0.60) over BLUE ($0.40), and squid prefers BLUE ($0.60) over cheap RED ($0.20). Privately, each participant sees their own valuations and a surplus calculator for any considered or observed trade, but does not see others’ values. They must infer who likes which chips from observed proposals and responses over just three short rounds.\n\nThe core efficiency pattern is: RED should flow from squid (who values it least) to badger and camel, and BLUE should flow from camel (who values it least) toward badger and squid. GREEN is neutral at $0.50 for everyone and may serve as a balancing chip or remain unused. Because each player only knows their own values, early proposals likely reveal tentative guesses: simple, small, or symmetric trades that appear plausibly fair. Personas matter for acceptance behavior: camel is very tolerant of small gains and unlikely to reject positive-surplus deals; squid is cooperative and somewhat generous but still sensitive to value; badger is moderately fair but also somewhat selective about trades.\n\nStrategically, proposers want to craft offers that are clearly beneficial to themselves (as shown by their calculator) but also likely to give recipients at least a small gain, given unknown valuations. Offers that are too one-sided risk rejections from the more fairness-sensitive players, but overtly generous trades sacrifice value. Simultaneous responses plus random selection among multiple accepters create a mild coordination problem: if more than one responder sees a gain, they all may accept, and the proposer cannot choose the partner. Over three rounds, players can adjust based on observed acceptances and rejections, but there is limited time to fully learn the others’ preferences. A plausible trajectory is conservative, low-stakes trades in Round 0 that start to move RED from squid to camel/badger and BLUE from camel to squid/badger; modestly more targeted and confident trades in Round 1 once patterns emerge; and final, opportunistic or clean-up trades in Round 2, focusing on any remaining obvious arbitrage while avoiding complex or risky proposals.",
