l. Dolphin has strong demand for blue and weaker demand for red; he can profit by buying blue from Whale (cheap to her, valuable to him) and selling red to Whale or Duck if he later infers their red is highly valued. Duck has high value on red and moderate value on blue; she will be interested in trades where she gives away some blue or possibly green to obtain red, and she may also accept trades that give her more blue if the price in red or green is modest.\n\nUncertainty and three-player competition introduce complications: when a trade would be profitable for more than one responder, multiple acceptance is possible, and a random recipient is chosen. That dilutes the expected value of proposing \"too attractive\" deals. Proposers must balance making offers generous enough to ensure at least one acceptance against keeping them narrow enough that not everyone wants to jump in. Over three rounds, players may shift from exploratory trades—probing others’ tastes—to more targeted surplus-extracting proposals once some patterns are revealed. Since the horizon is short and all are relatively acceptance-prone, the game is likely to see several executed trades that move chips from low- to high-value holders, especially reallocating red from Dolphin to Whale/Duck and blue from Whale/Duck to Dolphin, with green serving mostly as a low-risk, focal medium in early tests or as a tie-breaker when valuations for red and blue are closer.",
