iation or reputation. Early accepted trades will reveal some coarse information about relative valuations (for example, someone eagerly trading away red may hint that red is relatively low value to them), which can shape slightly more targeted proposals in later rounds. Still, short horizon and random recipient resolution keep the environment noisy, so most proposals remain simple, symmetric-looking exchanges that plausibly benefit either non-sender.\n\nGiven the specific valuations, frog-blue-6296 has the strongest motive to acquire blue and is willing to pay with green or red; fox-green-2854 also favors blue over red but has less spread between them; bat-pink-1751 values red and blue equally and green slightly less, making her roughly indifferent between red and blue and willing to trade green away for either. Efficient trades generally move blue chips toward frog and fox, and red chips away from fox. However, because nobody directly observes others' values, we forecast modest, roughly balanced trades: 1–3 chips per deal, often involving green as the selling color and blue or red as the purchased color. Across the three rounds, we expect a small number of accepted trades that gradually shift blue chips toward frog and fox and red chips slightly toward bat, with occasional declined offers when the proposer misjudges what will be attractive to at least one counterpart.",
