as imply:\n- Badger: relatively cooperative, low rejection thresholds; willing to accept modest gains and propose somewhat fair, not ultra-aggressive, trades. High uncertainty aversion suggests avoiding complicated or borderline proposals.\n- Peacock: highly strategic and numerate, with medium fairness thresholds and moderate rejection propensity. Likely to search for clearly positive-sum trades and avoid giving others too much surplus.\n- Unicorn: has a history of accepting even very low shares and rarely rejecting in ultimatum games; likely to accept almost any positive-value trade and may propose quite self-serving deals but is also highly cooperative, potentially tolerating small personal gains if beneficial to others.\n\nGiven only 3 rounds and no enforceable long-term relationship, players will likely prioritize clear private gains over exploring others' values. Expect the most transparent mispricing—Peacock’s cheap blue and Unicorn’s cheap red—to be exploited if noticed, generating blue-for-red swaps. Badger will probably focus on acquiring blue and unloading some red, but may get fewer trades if Peacock and Unicorn quickly discover their very strong red/blue complementarity and primarily trade with each other. Some profitable green-for-red or green-for-blue trades may appear as simple, low-risk experiments, especially early on when uncertainty about others’ values is highest.\n\nOverall forecast: at least a couple of accepted trades, concentrated on red/blue swaps involving Peacock and Unicorn; Badger secures at least one modestly profitable trade but may miss the highest-surplus opportunities among the other two. Strategic uncertainty about who will accept and random recipient selection will occasionally cause a proposer’s intended partner to miss out, but responders’ low rejection thresholds mean most clearly positive proposals to at least one non-sender will tend to be accepted.",
