alytically strategic and has a very strong incentive to accumulate blue, which is worth $0.70 to them. They will actively look for opportunities to buy blue cheaply in terms of value, especially from dog, for whom blue is relatively weak. Because they are fair-minded but less generous than dog, they may attempt slightly asymmetric but not blatantly unfair deals that others will still accept.\n\nBargaining dynamics over the three rounds likely follow this path: Round 0 is exploratory and fairness-anchored; players test simple small-size trades, especially involving green because its value is known by all. Dog may reveal a willingness to engage in low-margin but kind trades. Mouse and owl watch each other’s and dog’s revealed preferences—who eagerly buys or sells particular colors—to infer valuations. Round 1 sees more targeted trades: once owl or mouse suspect that dog undervalues blue relative to them, they may offer dog red or green for blue. Players also face the constraint of one proposal per turn and a total of only three rounds; because the horizon is short, they will accept any clearly positive-value deal that doesn’t seem exploitative. Round 2 is effectively a closing phase: each player, especially owl, tries to make a final consolidation move toward their best-valued chips, while dog continues to accept modestly beneficial offers.\n\nGiven simultaneous private responses and random selection among multiple acceptors, proposers cannot choose partners, which slightly discourages making highly skewed deals that might attract multiple acceptances (creating risk of trading with the wrong partner). Because everyone sees their own net gain or loss before deciding, accepted trades are assumed to be weakly value-improving for both parties. Across the full game, we therefore expect a moderate but not fully efficient concentration of blue in owl’s hands and some movement of blue out of dog’s inventory, with green and red sometimes serving as fair-looking payment media. 